	abstract = {This chapter presents the design, fabrication, and performance of the charged couple device (CCD) images. Decrease in transfer inefficiency over the surface-channel CCD technology is generally accepted to be at least an order of magnitude. Because of the fact that these commercially available devices are primarily line-scan image sensors and two-dimensional arrays with intrinsic silicon spectral response, it is intentional that there will be a heavy emphasis on these types of devices. The modulation-transfer function describes the fidelity of an imaging system by giving the attenuation of an image signal as a function of spatial frequency. In CCD image sensors, the MTF is the result of several parameters: the photo element aperture, the optical cross talk, the charge-transfer inefficiency, and the preamplifier characteristics. An n-channel CCD line-scan image sensor can be fabricated much like a high-density NMOS memory device. They both use two levels of polysilicon gates. Ion implantation is essential as a means of doping and is used at least twice in the course of making a typical two-phase device: once to form the n-channel and again to form the barriers that are located under the gaps in the first level of poly-Si along the CCD registers. A CCD signal-processing device that could appropriately be used in a camera for image processing is considered for application in spacecraft navigation and camera pointing. A significant feature of this technology is the high uniformity of response that is possible in the case of illumination from the silicon side.},
